{"parse":{"title":"History of Bariq","pageid":38959786,"revid":856810454,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"toccolours\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" align=\"right\" width=\"230px\" style=\"margin:\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<th style=\"background:#ccccff\">History of Bariq\n</th></tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"font-size: 100%;\">\n<p><big><b> Ancient History</b></big>\n</p>\n<ul><li>Period of 2000 BC.. - 250</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Semitic_people\" title=\"Semitic people\">Semitic</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Sheba\" title=\"Sheba\">Sheba</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Himyarite_Kingdom\" title=\"Himyarite Kingdom\">\u1e24imyar</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Bariq\" title=\"Bariq\">Bariq</a></li></ul>\n<p><big><b><a href=\"/wiki/Islam\" title=\"Islam\">The first Islamic covenants</a></b></big>\n</p>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Rashidun\" title=\"Rashidun\">Rashidun</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Umayyad_Caliphate\" title=\"Umayyad Caliphate\">Umayyad Caliphate</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Abbasid_Caliphate\" title=\"Abbasid Caliphate\">Abbasid Caliphate</a></li></ul>\n<p><big><b> Modern phases </b></big>\n</p>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Ottoman_Empire\" title=\"Ottoman Empire\">Ottoman Empire</a></li></ul>\n<p><big><b>Between two phases </b></big>\n</p>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Emirate_of_Diriyah\" title=\"Emirate of Diriyah\">The First Saudi State</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad_ibn_Ali_al-Idrisi\" title=\"Muhammad ibn Ali al-Idrisi\">Idrisids</a></li></ul>\n<p><big><b><a href=\"/wiki/Saudi_Arabia\" title=\"Saudi Arabia\">Saudi Arabia</a></b></big>\n</p>\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Bariq</b> (also <a href=\"/wiki/Romanization_of_Arabic\" title=\"Romanization of Arabic\">transliterated</a> as <b>Barik</b> or <b>Bareq</b>, <a href=\"/wiki/Arabic_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Arabic language\">Arabic</a>: <span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0642</span>&#8206;) was founded in 220 AD. It is part of the territory known historically as <a href=\"/wiki/Yemen\" title=\"Yemen\">Yemen</a>, which dates back to the second millennium BC. It was inhabited by immigrant tribes of southern Yemen called <a href=\"/wiki/Bariq\" title=\"Bariq\">Bariq</a>, who belong to the ancient tribe <a href=\"/wiki/Al-Azd\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Al-Azd\">Al-Azd</a> which has many clans linked to it.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Introduction\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Introduction</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Bariq_Establishment\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bariq Establishment</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Introduction\">Introduction</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Bariq&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Introduction\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Bariq was known before the advent of Islam as Badiyar Bariq (<a href=\"/wiki/Arabic_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Arabic language\">Arabic</a>: <span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">\u0628\u062f\u064a\u0627\u0631 \u0628\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0642</span>&#8206;), and it formed part of the old commercial route from Yemen to Mecca and the Levant, a regular seasonal journey.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> This also held <a href=\"/wiki/Suq_Hubasha\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Suq Hubasha\">Suq Hubasha</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> in the first month of <a href=\"/wiki/Rajab\" title=\"Rajab\">Rajab</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> which was the main market for Azd. Both the market and convoys were protected by the <a href=\"/wiki/Bareq\" title=\"Bareq\">Bareq</a> country. Suq Habasha was perhaps the greatest Arab souq and also the last of the <a href=\"/wiki/Jahiliyyah\" title=\"Jahiliyyah\">Jahiliyyah</a> (pre-<a href=\"/wiki/Islamic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Islamic\">Islamic</a>) markets to be destroyed.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>In the mid-seventh century AD, tribes from Bariq adopted Islam and played a pivotal role in <a href=\"/wiki/Muslim_conquests\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Muslim conquests\">the Islamic conquests</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> settling in many countries after the Muslim conquest.<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-17\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-17\">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-18\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-18\">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Bariq has been mentioned by many historians of the Islamic era and Arab writers such as <a href=\"/wiki/Ibn_Ishaq\" title=\"Ibn Ishaq\">Ibn Ishaq</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Hisham_Ibn_Al-Kalbi\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hisham Ibn Al-Kalbi\">Ibn Al-Kalbi</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ibn_Hisham\" title=\"Ibn Hisham\">Ibn Hisham</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ya%27qubi\" title=\"Ya&#39;qubi\">Ya'qubi</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Al-Baladhuri\" title=\"Al-Baladhuri\">Al-Baladhuri</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Khalifa_ibn_Khayyat\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Khalifa ibn Khayyat\">ibn Khayyat</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad_ibn_Jarir_al-Tabari\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Muhammad ibn Jarir al-Tabari\">al-Tabari</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ibn_Duraid\" title=\"Ibn Duraid\">Ibn Duraid</a> and others.<sup id=\"cite_ref-19\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-19\">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The first mentioning of Bariq in ancient geography books was from <a href=\"/wiki/Ab%C5%AB_Muhammad_al-Hasan_al-Hamd%C4%81n%C4%AB\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ab\u016b Muhammad al-Hasan al-Hamd\u0101n\u012b\">H\u0101md\u0101ni</a>'s book <i>Geography of the Arabian Peninsula</i>. <a href=\"/wiki/Yaqut_al-Hamawi\" title=\"Yaqut al-Hamawi\">al-Hamawi</a> also mentioned Bariq in his book.<sup id=\"cite_ref-20\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-20\">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bariq_Establishment\">Bariq Establishment</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Bariq&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Bariq Establishment\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Bariq dates back to 4,000 years ago. It was first inhabited by Hwaila ebn yaktan and his dynasty. It later joined the Sheba Kingdom during the 4th century B.C. and was ruled by the Himyarite Kingdom during the first century B.C.<sup id=\"cite_ref-21\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Bariq&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Bariq\" title=\"Bariq\">Bariq</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Province_of_Bariq\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Province of Bariq\">Province of Bariq</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Bariq&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Ulrich, Brain John (2008). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=2yROvV2N0QMC&amp;hl=ar&amp;source=gbs_navlinks_s\"><i>Constructing Al-Azd: Tribal Identity and Society in The Early Islamic Centuries</i></a>. <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Wisconsin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"University of Wisconsin\">University of Wisconsin</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Madison,Wisconsin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Madison,Wisconsin\">Madison,Wisconsin</a>: c2008. p.&#160;290. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780549634430\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780549634430\">9780549634430</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Constructing+Al-Azd%3A+Tribal+Identity+and+Society+in+The+Early+Islamic+Centuries.&amp;rft.place=University+of+Wisconsin+Madison%2CWisconsin&amp;rft.pages=290&amp;rft.pub=c2008&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.isbn=9780549634430&amp;rft.aulast=Ulrich&amp;rft.aufirst=Brain+John&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D2yROvV2N0QMC%26hl%3Dar%26source%3Dgbs_navlinks_s&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+Bariq\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=kPgNAQAAMAAJ&amp;q=bariq+Ma&#39;rib&amp;dq=bariq+Ma&#39;rib&amp;hl=ar&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=WlpXUffyN46v7Abxp4C4Cg&amp;ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA\">Bahrain through the ages: the history</a>\u060c</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=OvB6lbYcAqIC&amp;pg=PA91&amp;dq=bariq+azd&amp;hl=ar&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=PV5XUaWEI6iV7Aatp4D4BQ&amp;ved=0CFEQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&amp;q=bariq%20azd&amp;f=false\">Excellence and precedence: medieval Islamic discourse on legitimate leadership</a>\u060c</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?ei=8_cXUfbONpGChQeiqYH4Ag&amp;hl=ar&amp;id=XX1IAAAAMAAJ&amp;dq=%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%82+%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B4%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A1+%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D9%8A%D9%81&amp;q=%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%82#search_anchor\">\u0625\u064a\u0644\u0627\u0641 \u0642\u0631\u064a\u0634 \u0631\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u062a\u0627\u0621 \u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u064a\u0641</a>\u060c</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=q_189OeDwSMC&amp;pg=PA66&amp;dq=Azd+Barik&amp;hl=ar&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=_n_dT_3QO-qw6AHi-qSLCw&amp;ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&amp;q=Azd%20Barik&amp;f=false\">Encyclopaedic Ethnography of Middle-East and Central Asia</a>\u060c</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=VWL-_hRsm2IC&amp;pg=PA123&amp;dq=bariq+azd+6+day&amp;hl=ar&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=40tXUdP3J-LA7AaLloH4Bw&amp;redir_esc=y#v=onepage&amp;q=bariq%20azd%20&amp;f=false\">Meccan trade and the rise of Islam p123</a>\u060c</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?ei=eqQaUYupJ-GO0AXY3oCoDA&amp;hl=ar&amp;id=z21PAQAAIAAJ&amp;dq=%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%82+%D8%AD%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B4%D8%A9&amp;q=%D8%AD%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B4%D8%A9#search_anchor\">\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0645 \u0639\u0646\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628 \u0642\u0628\u0644 \u06